.TH \f3include-tidy\fP 1 "March 31, 2026" "PJL TOOLS"
.SH NAME
include-tidy \(em \f(CW#include\fP tidier
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B include-tidy
.BI "[-Xtidy " tidy-option ]...
.BI [ clang-option ]...
.I source-file
.br
.B include-tidy
.I other-option
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B include-tidy
is a command-line tool
that can be used to ``tidy'' the
\f(CW#include\fP directives
used in a \f(CW.c\fP file
by ensuring that it directly includes
header files where every symbol referenced
is declared.
.SH OPTIONS
.B include-tidy
has three kinds of command-line options:
.nr step 1 1
.IP \n[step]. 3
.BR include-tidy -specific
options.
.IP \n+[step].
.BR clang (1)
options.
.IP \n+[step].
Other options.
.SS Include-Tidy-Specific Options
All
.BR include-tidy -specific
options are preceded by an
.B -Xtidy
option to distinguish them from
.BR clang (1)
options.
.PP
An option argument
.I f
means
.IR file ,
.I n
means
.IR "unsigned integer" ,
and
.I s
means
.IR string .
.SS Clang Options
Options that are neither one of
.B "Other Options"
nor preceded by
.B -Xtidy
are
.BR clang (1)
options
and are passed to
.B clang
(libclang)
verbatim.
.SS Other Options
These options are given directly as-is.
.TP 5
.BR \-\-help " | " \-h
Prints a help message
for command-line options
and exits.
.TP
.BR \-\-version " | " \-v
Prints the version number
and exits.
.SH EXIT STATUS
.PD 0
.IP 0
Success.
.IP 64
Command-line usage error.
.IP 65
Source file has one or more errors.
.IP 66
Open file error.
.IP 69
Either could not invoke
.BR clang (1)
or get the current working directory.
.IP 70
Internal software error.
(Please report the bug.)
.IP 71
Operating system error.
.IP 74
I/O error.
.IP 78
Configuration file error.
.PD
.SH ENVIRONMENT
.TP
.B HOME
Used to locate a default configuration file
under the user's home directory.
If unset,
the home directory is obtained from the password database entry
for the effective user.
If that fails,
no default configuration file
under the user's home directory
is read.
.TP
.B XDG_CONFIG_DIRS
If set to a colon separated list of paths,
then for each
.I path
in it,
the first of
.IB path /include-tidy
to exist
and be readable
is used as the configuration file
(see
.BR include-tidy (5)).
.TP
.B XDG_CONFIG_HOME
If set to a path
of a directory
and
.B $XDG_CONFIG_HOME/include-tidy
exists and is readable,
then that used as the configuration file
(see
.BR include-tidy (5)).
.SH FILES
.TP
.B $XDG_CONFIG_HOME/include-tidy
.PD 0
.TP
.B ~/.config/include-tidy
.TP
.B /etc/xdg/include-tidy
.PD
The default configuration file.
